05989nam a22011055i 9781512823387DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815128233877 a10.9783/97815128233872doi  a(DE-B1597)633111  a(OCoLC)1343103926  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBF789.C7 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a296.16223/eng/202206271 aSagiv, Gadi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJewish Blues :bA History of a Color in Judaism /cGadi Sagiv. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (252 p.) :b14 color images (insert)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Materiality of Blue in Premodern Judaism -- tChapter 2. Tekhelet in Medieval Jewish Mysticism: Cosmology, Theology, and Vision -- tChapter 3. Blue Garments in Early Modern Judaism: Between Kabbalistic Symbolism and Social Practice -- tChapter 4. The Modern Renaissance of the Tekhelet Dye -- tChapter 5. Reactions to Modern Tekhelet: Blue as a Sociocultural Challenge -- tConclusion -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJewish Blues presents a broad cultural, social, and intellectual history of the color blue in Jewish life between the sixteenth and twenty-first centuries. Bridging diverse domains such as religious law, mysticism, eschatology, as well as clothing and literature, this book contends that, by way of a protracted process, the color blue has constituted a means through which Jews have understood themselves.In ancient Jewish texts, the term for blue, tekhelet, denotes a dye that serves Jewish ritual purposes. Since medieval times, however, Jews gradually ceased to use tekhelet in their ritual life. In the nineteenth century, however, interest in restoring ancient dyes increased among European scholars. In the Jewish case, rabbis and scientists attempted to reproduce the ancient tekhelet dye. The resulting dyes were gradually accepted in the ritual life of many Orthodox Jews. In addition to being a dye playing a role in Jewish ritual, blue features prominently in the Jewish mystical tradition, in Jewish magic and popular custom, and in Jewish eschatology. Blue is also representative of the Zionist movement, and it is the only chromatic color in the national flag of the State of Israel.Through the study of the changing roles and meanings attributed to the color blue in Judaism, Jewish Blues sheds new light on the power of a visual symbol in shaping the imagination of Jews throughout history. The use of the color blue continues to reflect pressing issues for Jews in our present era, as it has become a symbol of Jewish modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCabalaxColor. 0aColor. 0aColorsxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aSymbolism of colors. 4aHistory of Jewish People and Culture. 4aInterdisciplinary-Jewish Studies. 4aReligion-Judaism. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aIsaac Herzog.  aJewish Enlightenment.  aJewish history.  aState of Israel.  abible.  aclothing.  aculture.  adye.  ahasidism hasidic.  akabbalah.  amagic.  amedieval.  amessianism messianic.  amodern.  amysticism.  aorthodox.  arabbinic.  asymbolism.  atabernacle.  atassels.  atekhelet.  atemple.  atheocracy.  atsitsit.  azionism zionist.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE